dover the weekend to restructure the offer ``as rapidly as we can,''a pilots union spokesman said. Banks balked at financing the $6.75billion cash offer for UAL Corp. led by the Air Line PilotsAssociation and a management group, and the announcement Fridaythat the bid had fallen through triggered the sharpest stock marketdrop since the crash of 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The huge Mexican glass company Vitro SA saysit has signed a definitive agreement to buy Anchor Class ContainerCorp. and Latchford Glass Co. of California for more than $900million.   The Anchor deal, valued at about $800 million, would be thelargest Mexican takeover of a U.S. company, Vitro said Sunday.   Vitro's protracted effort to take over Tampa-based Anchor, thenation's second-largest glass company, won approval by Anchor'sdirectors after the glass giant raised its cash tender offer forAnchor stock from $20 to $21.25 a share. Anchor's board ofdirectors in August rejected the $20-a-share bid.</TEXT><DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Union workers at Boeing Co.'s helicopter divisionhave approved an indefinite contract extension at theirPennsylvania plant, avoiding a strike that has hit Boeing plantselsewhere.   No negotiations were scheduled in the nearly 2-week-old strikeby machinists, but contract talks were set to begin Monday betweenBoeing and its second-largest union, representing engineers andtechnical workers.   Members of United Aerospace Workers Local 1069, which representsabout 3,200 hourly production and maintenance workers at BoeingHelicopters' suburban Philadelphia plant, approved their extensionSunday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A sharp rise in energy costs helped trigger arebound in wholesale price inflation in September, wiping out threerare monthly declines this summer, the government said.   The 0.9 percent increase Friday in the Labor Department'sProducer Price Index, measuring inflation one stop short of theretail level, represented a return to the high inflation ratesexperienced in the first five months of the year.   In another economic report, the Commerce Department said retailsales rose a stronger-than-expected 0.5 percent last month, theseventh consecutive rise.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A plunge in General Motors Corp. car and lighttruck sales led an 11.9 percent decline in early-October vehiclesales by domestic automakers compared with last year, the companiessaid.   The eight major companies making vehicles in North America saidFriday their cars and light trucks sold at an average rate of30,734 a day during the Oct. 1-10 period this year, compared with34,867 during the same time last year.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Economic growth in 1990 will slump toits slowest pace in eight years with an outright recession adistinct threat unless the Federal Reserve lowers interest rates,the nation's top business executives forecast.   The Business Council, composed of the chief executives of 100 ofthe country's largest corporations, said Friday the economy beganto lose steam this summer. They predicted the sluggish period wouldlast through much of next year.</TEXT><DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Young andamp; Rubicam, one of the nation'slargest advertising agencies, pleaded innocent to charges it paidnearly $1 million in bribes to Jamaican officials for the island'slucrative tourism campaign.   Two of the company's executives and a former executive alsopleaded innocent Friday in U.S. District Court Friday.   Young andamp; Rubicam faces up to $7.5 million in fines if it isconvicted. Young andamp; Rubicam still holds the Jamaica account, whichwon praise for its theme ''Come Back to Jamaica,'' and hasvigorously denied any wrongdoing.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The biggest selloff since the crash of 1987 rocked the stockmarket Friday, driving prices into a free-fall decline followingnews that a big buyout deal for UAL Corp. had fallen through. TheDow Jones average of 30 industrials plunged 190.58 points, or 6.91percent, to 2,569.26.   Currency dealers pounded down the dollar in hectic sellingincited by the stock plunge.   Bond prices rocketed higher in heavy trading afternoon asinvestors fled the panicky stock market.   Tumbling stock prices triggered temporary trading halts forstock-index futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, in a dropthat mirrored a near- record selloff on Wall Street; orange juicefutures plunged; and crude oil futures jumped higher.</TEXT></DOC>